ion and histone wrapping. Not even mentioning mitochondrial dna or prenatal development factors.<\/p>\n\n<p>Instead: A good diet and exercise. <\/p>\n","answer_id":14541,"question_id":14540,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1390267976},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2442ea911c89187262d6575d739a1ca7?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5148,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5148/swbarnes2","reputation":1824,"display_name":"swbarnes2"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1390329009,"creation_date":1390328305,"body":"<blockquote>\n  <p>As far as I know, the DNA sequence becomes shorter every time a cell\n  divides. A shorter sequence results in information loss and aging\n  characteristics.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Neither telomeres nor aging are nearly that simple.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>is it already possible to perfectly reproduce the DNA?<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>No.  <strong>Any<\/strong> method that would be used to replicate DNA requires using enzymes, and they always have a non zero failure rate.  You could use whole genome amplification to make a pile of DNA that was on average the right sequence, but each individual chromosome would have errors.  And forget copying over epigenetic modifications.<\/p>\n\n<p>There are ways to get cells to incorporate new DNA, but every cell in an organ of a living organism?  And a whole mammalian genome's worth?  And to magically tell the cell that the new genome should replace the old one?<\/p>\n\n<p>None of that is feasible.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>(I found articles about bacteria inserting pieces of DNA into human\n  cells)<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Okay, let's get some scale here.  Most bacteria have a genome of 5-10 million bases.  Humans have a genome of 3 billion bases.  Even if a bacteria can transduce a small plasmid into a human cell, that doesn't scale up to bacteria replacing the whole genome of every cell in an organ.<\/p>\n\n<p>And because there's always a relevant xkcd comic<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://xkcd.com/793/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://xkcd.com/793/<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":14548,"question_id":14540,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1390329009}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/14540/stay-young-by-reinserting-own-dna-from-years-ago","last_activity_date":1390329009,"creation_date":1390260952,"answer_count":2,"title":"Stay young by reinserting own DNA from years ago?","body":"<p>As far as I know, the DNA sequence becomes shorter every time a cell divides.<br>\nA shorter sequence results in information loss and aging characteristics.<br>\n<br>\nAs a countermeasure, shouldn't one stay young and healthy at least longer, if the DNA in a cell is changed with a \"better\" DNA (from years ago... let's say your DNA was extracted with the age of 20 and you reinsert it every 10 years or so)?\n<br><br><\/p>\n\n<p>If this is true, then (as for today's technology)<br>\n- is it already possible to perfectly reproduce the DNA? (I only found articles about XNA)<br>\n- is it possible to easily replace the DNA in all human cells? (I found articles about bacteria inserting pieces of DNA into human cells)<\/p>\n","question_id":14540,"tags":["dna","reproduction","dna-damage"],"score":2,"accepted_answer_id":14541,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":187,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b227c6c2c91f7248998801b23712314a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1114,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1114/kal","reputation":505,"display_name":"Kal","accept_rate":29},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":0,"post_id":14532,"edited":false,"crea