omness and, say, pseudorandomness is crucial. If reality is pseudorandom then things <i>are<\/i> inevitable. If reality is random then things might be less inevitable. So, <i>for the purpose of this question<\/i>, we need to acknowledge that we really don&#39;t know about this aspect of reality (and usually we wouldn&#39;t care, because for normal questions it doesn&#39;t matter one iota)."},{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user3395"},"score":0,"post_id":14454,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/njNrp.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5407,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5407/dapeng-gao","reputation":135,"display_name":"Dapeng Gao"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1389679538,"comment_id":19147,"body":"@Peter No, I don&#39;t think that there is much quantum-mechanical instability in DNA beyond chemistry. I therefore assume that there is no significant accumulation or amplification of quantum-mechanical randomness, if any."},{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user3395"},"score":0,"post_id":14454,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/njNrp.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5407,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5407/dapeng-gao","reputation":135,"display_name":"Dapeng Gao"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1389679878,"comment_id":19148,"body":"@Peter Although I would certainly like that particular claim evaluated by a chemical-biologist."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/njNrp.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5407,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5407/dapeng-gao","reputation":135,"display_name":"Dapeng Gao"},"score":0,"post_id":14454,"edited":false,"creation_date":1389713986,"comment_id":19157,"body":"Assuming randomness is certainly a proper model for scientific researches. You say that in this question, the distinction between randomness and pseudorandomness is crucial, and 