unt":0,"last_activity_date":1387485533,"creation_date":1387485533,"body":"<p>I suspect you will struggle to find what you are looking for.  However, you could break down your search criteria into smaller chunks to come up with some more successful (but still incomplete) results.  For example, species of what?  Do you really want ALL species (e.g.  Bacteria, Archaea, Eukaryota)?  Do you want just species that are currently alive (extant) or all species that are know to have existed at some point?  Do you want sub-species?<\/p>\n\n<p>Once you have decided on such things, you may be better off searching for individual country databases.  If you do decide you want ALL species, I suggest you break down each search into smaller chunks - such as 'mammalia'.  <\/p>\n","answer_id":14073,"question_id":14059,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9f137c8bccd23ae845550c5e95c1e31b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4821,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4821/rodrigo","reputation":478,"display_name":"Rodrigo"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1389300629,"creation_date":1389300629,"body":"<p>Have you tried ITIS?<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.itis.gov/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.itis.gov/<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>I once used their database. It was in MS Access format.<\/p>\n","answer_id":14367,"question_id":14059,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/14059/is-there-a-downloadable-list-of-all-species-along-with-their-traditional-classif","last_activity_date":1389300629,"creation_date":1387404870,"answer_count":3,"title":"Is there a downloadable list of all species along with their traditional classification?","body":"<p>I'm looking for a downloadable list of all known (or better said, online documented) species in this straightforward format, as an example the European Frog:<\/p>\n\n<p>Kingdom: Animalia<br>\nDivision: Chordata<br>\nClass: Amp