d":14350,"up_vote_count":3},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0348be8a2ca783679f79cd6b0754da14?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4140,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4140/j-alfred-prufrock","reputation":651,"display_name":"J. Alfred Prufrock"},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":1,"post_id":14362,"edited":false,"creation_date":1389290655,"comment_id":18933,"body":"<i>&quot; In culture, antibiotic-resistant bacterial strains grow essentially as fast as non-resistant strains.&quot;<\/i>.. Antibiotic resistance does pose and additional cost on growth.. It might be difficult to observe it in a gross scale.. However it is true that that resistant strains must have optimized the protein synthesis machinery as much as possible to minimize cost."}],"down_vote_count":1,"last_activity_date":1389288874,"creation_date":1389288874,"body":"<p>In short, yes. Perhaps the best way of thinking about antibiotic resistance is not to think of there being 'antibiotic resistance' genes at all, but rather ordinary alleles that are vertically transferred in the typical fashion until at a certain time a deleterious chemical agent is introduced and one specific allele just happens to mitigate the effects of that chemical. It is less a matter of competition than it is of blind chance. Now of course, in principle, the lucky genetic element that will ensure survival may come with an increased energy cost as opposed to the 'wild-type' genome expression, but considering the general mechanisms of antibiotic resistance, one or two extra gene products, maybe a slightly less active enzyme, an extra membrane transporter, the cost is typically not excessive. In culture, antibiotic-resistant bacterial strains grow essentially as fast as non-resistant strains. <\/p>\n\n<p>Now concerning the retaining of the resistance after removal of the antibiotic, if the gene is integrated into the genome with the proper regulatory apparatus, it can remain in the species essentially forever. In the case of plasmids or other mobile genetic elements, bacteria do tend to lose these through random processes between divisions, however, many of these elements do have mechanisms to preserve (plasmid addiction) and propagate themselves (horizontal gene transfer). <\/p>\n\n<p>The most important thing to remember about resistance, however, is that only an infinitesimally small proportion of the population actually needs the resistance genetic element to actually start a new resistant population upon antibiotic introduction.<\/p>\n","answer_id":14362,"question_id":14350,"up_vote_count":3},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2442ea911c89187262d6575d739a1ca7?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5148,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5148/swbarnes2","reputation":1824,"display_name":"swbarnes2"},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/f0PGT.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3615,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3615/biogirl","reputation":3923,"display_name":"biogirl","accept_rate":89},"score":0,"post_id":14365,"edited":false,"creation_date":1389372974,"comment_id":18982,"body":"Totally agree with the last sentence. They ARE there and they ARE bad."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0abe51a9fcb000452afeb44794afa531?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1169,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1169/zab","reputation":118,"display_name":"ZAB"},"score":0,"post_id":14365,"edited":false,"creation_date":1391003019,"comment_id":19615,"body":"How long will XDR tuberculosis and MSRA Staph last if we