e). However, the frequency of transposition events is low, and the difference in amount of DNA between different cells in an individual is low. When you reason at the level of different individuals, however, the proportion of genome affected by transposable elements may be relatively high (give a look <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17300983\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a> for a reference)<\/p>\n","answer_id":14240,"question_id":11371,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1388915189}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/11371/transposons-and-the-net-amount-of-dna","last_activity_date":1388915189,"creation_date":1383880055,"answer_count":1,"title":"Transposons and the net amount of DNA","body":"<p>The <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Retrotransposon\" rel=\"nofollow\">retrotransposons<\/a> and certain <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transposable_element\" rel=\"nofollow\">DNA-transposons<\/a>, are \"jumping\" sequences which may be incorporated elsewhere in the genomic DNA of an organism, through varying mechanisms. This insertion is almost random in case of retrotransposons and most DNA-transposons, but some transposing enzymes show specificity in selection of insertion sites. In either case, the \"copy-paste\" mechanism of transposition is essentially a random process(considering the frequency and place of transposition) and therefore, the extent of transposition should vary among all individuals, and all cells of a single individual. My question is,<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Is the extent of transposition random and varied among the different\n  somatic cells of an individual or is there a regulatory mechanism which ensures that\n  there is not much difference in the net content of DNA (caused by unequal transposition) by equalizing\n  the extent of transposition in different individuals or different\n  cells of the same individual? If not, does this unequal c-value in different cell cause any troubles?<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n","question_id":11371,"tags":["molecular-biology","dna","molecular-genetics"],"score":3,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":104,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1386261783},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/YMlKc.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3776,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3776/satwik-pasani","reputation":2491,"display_name":"Satwik Pasani","accept_rate":68},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":7,"post_id":10809,"edited":false,"creation_date":1381378378,"comment_id":14373,"body":"THe tumors in brain are mostly glioblastoma. Neuroblastoma is rare."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/YMlKc.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3776,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3776/satwik-pasani","reputation":2491,"display_name":"Satwik Pasani","accept_rate":68},"score":0,"post_id":10809,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"edited":false,"creation_date":1381384115,"comment_id":14375,"body":"@WYSIWYG That is true, but, if I am not mistaken, the rarity of Neuroblastomas is lesser than the rarity of heart malignancies."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":10809,"edited":false,"creation_date":1381389055,"comment_id":14378,"body":"neuroblastoma is more common in infancy and early childhood when there are a lot of neural progenitors. 